[[File:Ladyshore irwell old supports.jpg|thumb|right|200px|The bridge supports on the river. The bleach works were to the right of this image as it looks west.]] '''Lever Bank Bleach Works''' was a [[Bleachfield|Bleach Works]] at Ladyshore, near [[Little Lever]], [[Bolton]]. The works was owned by Thomas Ridgway & Sons. Former British [[Prime Minister]] [[Tony Blair]] would appear to be a direct descendent of this family.<ref>{{cite web | title= This is Lancashire | work= Blair's family tree has branches in Bolton! | url= http://archive.thisislancashire.co.uk/1997/5/13/828094.html | format= [[HTTP]] | accessdate= 2007-10-30 | deadurl= yes | archiveurl= https://archive.is/20080103072041/http://archive.thisislancashire.co.uk/1997/5/13/828094.html | archivedate= 2008-01-03 | df= }}</ref>
==Location== The works was located between the [[Manchester Bolton & Bury Canal]] to the north, and the [[River Irwell]] to the south, in the area known as [[Ladyshore]] in the [[Irwell Valley]].
[[File:Irwell weir.jpg|thumb|right|200px|The weir across the [[River Irwell]]. Water was diverted to the left of this image.]] [[File:Lever bank bleach works ladyshore.jpg|thumb|right|200px|The cobbled access road to the works, still in excellent condition although slightly overgrown.]] Accessed from Ladyshore Bridge, over the canal, the cobbled pathway is still very much evident. Stanchions across the river still stand although the bridge/pipework they supported no longer exists. A weir was built on the nearby [[River Irwell]] and water diverted through a small channel into a reservoir. High quality stone walls are still evident along the banks of the river.
The weir collapsed in June 2012.<ref>{{Citation | title = Historic weir falls victim to flooding | url = http://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/news/9815740.Historic_weir_falls_victim_to_flooding/ | publisher = [[theboltonnews.co.uk]] | date = 13 July 2012 | accessdate = 6 August 2012}}</ref>
