{{Other uses|Noren (surname)}} {{Italic title|reason=[[:Category:Japanese words and phrases]]}} [[File:Fabric shop in Nara.jpg|thumb|Traditional fabric shop in [[Nara, Nara|Nara]] with ''noren'' in front of the entrance]] [[File:Noren at a sento by udono in Yoyogi, Tokyo.jpg|thumb|''Noren'' with the ゆ sign, marking a bath house]] '''''Noren''''' (暖簾) are traditional [[Japan]]ese [[cloth|fabric]] dividers hung between rooms, on walls, in doorways, or in windows. They usually have one or more vertical slits cut from the bottom to nearly the top of the fabric, allowing for easier passage or viewing. ''Noren'' are rectangular and come in many different materials, sizes, colors, and patterns.
== Homes == Noren were originally used to protect a house from wind, dust, and rain, as well as to keep a house warm on cold days and to provide shade on hot summer days.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://matcha-jp.com/en/1933|title=Japanese Encyclopedia: Noren {{!}} MATCHA - JAPAN TRAVEL WEB MAGAZINE|last=MATCHA|work=MATCHA - JAPAN TRAVEL WEB MAGAZINE|access-date=2017-03-18|language=ja-JP}}</ref> They can also be used for decorative purposes or for dividing a room into two separate spaces.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thejapaneseshop.co.uk/blog/the-story-of-japanese-noren/|title=Japanese Noren {{!}} Uses & History of Japanese Noren|date=2013-09-27|work=The Japanese Shop Blog|access-date=2017-03-18|language=en-US}}</ref>
== Businesses == Exterior ''noren'' are traditionally used by shops and restaurants as a means of protection from sun, wind, and [[dust]], and for displaying a shop's name or [[logo]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}} Names are often Japanese characters, especially [[kanji]], but may be [[Mon (emblem)|mon]] emblems, [[Japanese rebus monogram]]s, or abstract designs. Noren designs are generally traditional to complement their association with traditional establishments, but modern designs also exist. Interior noren are often used to separate dining areas from kitchens or other preparation areas, which also prevents smoke or smells from escaping.
Because a ''noren'' often features the shop name or logo, the word in Japanese may also refer to a company's brand value. Most notably, in Japanese [[Accountancy|accounting]], the word ''noren'' is used to describe the [[Goodwill (accounting)|goodwill]] of a company after an acquisition.
[[Sentō]] (commercial bathhouses) also place ''noren'' across their entrances, typically blue in color for men and red for women with the [[kanji]] 湯 (yu, lit. hot water) or the corresponding [[hiragana]] ゆ. They are also hung in the front entrance to a shop to signify that the establishment is open for business, and they are always taken down at the end of the business day.
