[[File:Blauschimmelkäse IMGP5469 wp.jpg|thumb|right|Some cheeses, including varieties of blue cheese, are made from thermized milk.]] '''Thermization''', also spelled '''thermisation''', is a method of sanitizing [[raw milk]] with low heat. "Thermization is a generic description of a range of subpasteurization heat treatments (57 to 68°C × 10 to 20 s) that markedly reduce the number of spoilage bacteria in milk with minimal heat damage."<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.3168/jds.S0022-0302(07)72607-3 |pmid=17183074 |title=Lipolysis in Cheddar Cheese Made from Raw, Thermized, and Pasteurized Milks |journal=Journal of Dairy Science |volume=90 |issue=1 |pages=47–56 |year=2007 |last1=Hickey |first1=D.K. |last2=Kilcawley |first2=K.N. |last3=Beresford |first3=T.P. |last4=Wilkinson |first4=M.G. }}</ref> The process is not used on other food products,<ref name="Brennan" /> and is similar to [[pasteurization]] but uses lower temperatures, allowing the milk product to retain more of its original taste.<ref name="MV Voice">{{cite news|url=http://www.mv-voice.com/morgue/2003/2003_09_05.dinea.html|title=Keeping it raw|date=September 5, 2003|last=Rich|first=Robert|publisher=Embarcadero Publishing Company|work=The Mountain View Voice|accessdate=October 23, 2010}}</ref> In Europe, there is a distinction between cheeses made of thermized milk and raw-milk cheeses. However, the United States' [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) places the same regulations on all unpasteurized cheeses. As a result, cheeses from thermized milk must be aged for 60 days or more before being sold in the United States, the same restriction placed on raw-milk cheeses by the FDA.<ref name="SF Gate">{{cite news|url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2006-07-13/wine/17304107_1_blue-cheese-milk-cheese-sheep-s-milk|title=Wisconsin's Buttermilk Blue adds pizazz to summer salads|last=Fletcher|first=Janet|date=July 13, 2006|publisher=Hearst Communications Inc|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|accessdate=October 23, 2010}}</ref>
Thermization involves heating milk at temperatures of around {{convert|145|-|149|F|C}} for 15 seconds, while pasteurization involves heating milk at {{convert|160|F|C}} for 15 seconds or at {{convert|145|F|C}} for 30 minutes.<ref name="MV Voice" /> Thermization is used to extend the keeping quality of raw milk (the length of time that milk is suitable for consumption)<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.jbc.org/content/40/2/373.full.pdf|title=A method for the determination of the keeping quality of milk|last1=Baker|first1=John C.|last2=Van Slyke|first2=Lucius L.|date=December 1, 1919|journal=[[Journal of Biological Chemistry|The Journal of Biological Chemistry]]|volume=40|issue=2|pages=373}}</ref> when it cannot be immediately used in other products, such as cheese. Thermization can also be used to extend the storage life of [[fermented milk products]] by inactivating microorganisms in the product.<ref name="Sun" />
Thermization inactivates [[psychrotrophic bacteria]] in milk <ref name="Sun">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=8zWcTxxSqzEC&pg=PA274&dq=thermization#v=onepage&q=thermization&f=false|title=Thermal Food Processing: New Technologies and Quality Issues|last=Sun|first=Da-Wen|page=274|publisher=[[CRC Press]]|year=2006|isbn=978-1-57444-628-9}}</ref> and allows the milk to be stored below {{convert|8|C|F}} for three days,<ref name="Brennan" /> or stored at {{convert|0|-|1|C|F}} for seven days.<ref name="Early">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=BuR28Y-S4SMC&pg=PA13&dq=thermization#v=onepage&q=thermization&f=false|title=The Technology of Dairy Products|last=Early|first=Ralph|publisher=Springer|year=1998|pages=13–14|edition=2|isbn=978-0-7514-0344-2}}</ref> Later, the milk may be given stronger heat treatment to be preserved longer.<ref name="Brennan">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=3p5-YRvyHHgC&pg=PA48&lpg=PA48&dq=thermisation#v=onepage&q=thermisation&f=false|title=Food Processing Handbook|editor-last=Brennan|editor-first=James G.|page=48|publisher=Wiley-VCH|year=2006|isbn=978-3-527-30719-7}}</ref> Cooling thermized milk before reheating is necessary to delay/prevent the outgrowth of bacterial spores. When the milk is first heated, spores can begin to germinate, but their growth can be halted or delayed when the milk is refrigerated, depending on the microorganisms' growth requirements. Germinated spores are sensitive to subsequent heating, however since germination is not a homogeneous process, not all spores will germinate or be inactivated by subsequent heating.
